'''Luis de la Fuente Castillo''' (born 21 June 1961) is a Spanish [[association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]] and former professional player who played as a [[left-back]]. He is the manager of the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].

He amassed [[La Liga]] totals of 254 matches and six goals over 13 seasons, with [[Athletic Bilbao]] and [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], winning two league titles with the former including a [[Double (association football)|double]] with the [[Copa del Rey]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antena3.com/noticias/deportes/futbol/lado-personal-luis-fuente-discreto-familiar-elogiador-futbolistas-roja_20240710668ea32d099c8900015c3eff.html|title=El lado personal de Luis de la Fuente: discreto, familiar y elogiador de los futbolistas de la Roja|trans-title=The personal side of Luis de la Fuente: low profile, intimate and complimentary of the ''Roja'' footballers|publisher=[[Antena 3 (Spanish TV channel)|Antena 3]]|first=Rosario|last=Miñano|language=es|date=10 July 2024|access-date=11 July 2024}}</ref>

De la Fuente began working in the Spanish youth teams in 2013, managing the [[Spain national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] to victory in the [[2015 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2015 European Championship]] and the [[Spain national under-21 football team|under-21 side]] to the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2019 equivalent]]. He coached the [[Spain national under-23 football team|Olympic team]] to the silver medal at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 games]], and took over at the seniors in 2022, winning the [[2023 UEFA Nations League Finals|2023 Nations League]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].

==Playing career==
Born in [[Haro, La Rioja]], de la Fuente graduated from [[Athletic Bilbao]]'s youth system,<ref name=SUCCESS>{{cite news|url=https://www.elcomercio.es/deportes/juegos-olimpicos/espana/fuente-exito-tecnico-20210807103652-ntrc.html|title=De la Fuente, el éxito de un técnico discreto|trans-title=De la Fuente, the success of a low-key manager|newspaper=[[El Comercio (Spain)|El Comercio]]|first=Aser|last=Falagán|language=es|date=7 August 2021|access-date=16 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/deportes/futbol/2022/12/12/63950c7be4d4d8902a8b457b.html|title=La hora de Luis De la Fuente, el hijo del marino apasionado del Athletic, criado en una mercería y fan de Julio Iglesias: "Vamos a pasar de la noche al día"|trans-title=The moment of Luis De la Fuente, the son of the sailor passionate about Athletic Bilbao, raised in a haberdashery and a fan of Julio Iglesias: "We are going to go from night to day"|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|first=Inma|last=Lidón|language=es|date=12 December 2022|access-date=26 March 2026}}</ref> and made his senior debut with [[Athletic Bilbao B|the reserves]] in 1978, in the [[Segunda División B]]. On 8 March 1981, he made his first-team – and [[La Liga]] – debut, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 0–0 away draw against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1981/03/09/pagina-13/1064178/pdf.html#&mode=fullScreen|title=0–0: Abdicación valencianista ante el Athletic|trans-title=0–0: ''Valencianista'' abdication against Athletic|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|date=9 March 1981|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref>

De la Fuente was promoted to the main squad in the summer of 1982. He scored his first professional goal on 26 March 1983, closing the 4–0 home win over [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta de Vigo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1983/03/27/pagina-10/1084109/pdf.html#&mode=fullScreen|title=El Athletic, sin problemas|trans-title=Athletic, no problems|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Eduardo|last=Castañeda|language=es|date=27 March 1983|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref>

In July 1987, de la Fuente signed for fellow top-flight club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.sevilla.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/sevilla/abc.sevilla/1987/07/06/048.html|title=El lateral del Athletic De la Fuente firma hoy contrato por el Sevilla|trans-title=Athletic full-back De la Fuente signs contract with Sevilla today|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|first=Luis|last=Granado|language=es|date=6 July 1987|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> and continued to appear regularly the following campaigns in defence or as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left winger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.muchodeporte.com/sevilla-fc/66395/luis-de-la-fuente-el-seleccionador-al-que-una-tarjeta-echo-del-sevilla/|title=Luis de la Fuente: El seleccionador al que una tarjeta 'echó' del Sevilla|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente: The national team manager 'ousted' from Sevilla by a booking|publisher=Mucho Deporte|first=José Antonio|last=Jiménez|language=es|date=8 December 2022|access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref> In 1991, he returned to Athletic for a 20 million [[Spanish peseta|pesetas]] fee,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.sevilla.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/sevilla/abc.sevilla/1991/09/05/067.html|title=El Sevilla traspasa a De la Fuente al Athletic de Bilbao por veinte millones|trans-title=Sevilla transfer De la Fuente to Athletic de Bilbao for twenty millions|newspaper=ABC|language=es|date=5 September 1991|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> featuring rarely under coach [[Jupp Heynckes]] who arrived one year later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deia.eus/athletic/2019/05/15/luis-fuente-corazon-partido-vida-4782232.html|title=Luis de la Fuente: "No tengo el corazón partido, mi vida ha sido el Athletic"|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente: "My heart is not divided, Athletic has been my life"|newspaper=[[Deia (newspaper)|Deia]]|first=Pako|last=Ruiz|language=es|date=15 May 2019|access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref>

De la Fuente joined [[Deportivo Alavés|Alavés]] in 1993, with the side in the third tier. After [[1993–94 Segunda División B|one season]], he retired at the age of 33.<ref name=SUCCESS/>

==Coaching career==
===Early years===
De la Fuente's first managerial job was at [[Club Portugalete|Portugalete]], in [[Divisiones Regionales de Fútbol in the Basque Country|the regional leagues]]. In summer 2000, he was appointed at [[Segunda División B]] club [[CD Aurrerá de Vitoria|Aurrerá de Vitoria]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2000/09/02/pagina-37/685776/pdf.html#&mode=fullScreen|title=Una apuesta para dar un salto cualitativo|trans-title=A bet to make a jump of quality|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|language=es|date=2 September 2000|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> but was sacked in March of the following year in spite of a seventh place in the table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2001/03/14/pagina-30/432217/pdf.html#&mode=fullScreen|title=Los nervios afloran en el tramo final|trans-title=Nerves everywhere in final stretch|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Bruno|last=Parcero|language=es|date=14 March 2001|access-date=16 September 2021}}</ref>

After a spell back at Sevilla (academy), de la Fuente returned to Athletic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2005/06/21/mas_futbol/1119335241_850215.html|title=Luis de la Fuente, el último fichaje para Lezama|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente, last signing for Lezama|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=es|date=21 June 2005|access-date=16 June 2023}}</ref> Initially a manager of the youths and the reserves,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/4404/luis-de-la-fuente-new-bilbao-athletic-coach.html|title=Luis de la Fuente, new Bilbao Athletic coach|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=8 July 2006|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> he also acted as match delegate for two years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/news/5677/luis-de-la-fuente-the-new-delegate.html|title=Luis de la Fuente, the new delegate|publisher=Athletic Bilbao|date=16 July 2007|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> before returning to his previous duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://athletic.elcorreo.com/noticias/2009-07-08/luis-fuente-trabaja-bilbao-200907081331.html|title=Luis de la Fuente ya trabaja con el Bilbao Athletic|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente already works with Bilbao Athletic|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|language=es|date=8 July 2009|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref>

On 13 July 2011, de la Fuente was named Alavés coach,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/07/13/futbol/mas_futbol/1310558967.html|title=Luis de la Fuente retorna al Alavés como entrenador después de 17 años|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente returns to Alavés as a manager 17 years later|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=13 July 2011|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> being dismissed on 17 October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/10/16/futbol/mas_futbol/1318797576.html|title=El Alavés destituye a su técnico Luis de la Fuente|trans-title=Alavés dismiss their manager Luis de la Fuente|newspaper=Marca|first=Pablo|last=M. Otero|language=es|date=16 October 2011|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref>

===Spain youths===
On 5 May 2013, de la Fuente was appointed at the helm of the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain under-19 team]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://athletic.elcorreo.com/noticias/2013-05-05/federacion-espanola-ficha-luis-20130505.html|title=La Federación Española ficha a Luis De la Fuente, que dirigirá la Sub'19|trans-title=The Spanish Federation signs Luis De la Fuente, who will manage the under-19s|newspaper=El Correo|language=es|date=5 May 2013|access-date=12 October 2015}}</ref> who won the [[2015 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2015 UEFA European Championship]] in Greece.<ref name=U19>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/deportes/2015/07/20/55acdc9d46163f50718b4586.html|title=Los campeones Sub-19 ya están en España|trans-title=The Under-19 champions are already in Spain|newspaper=El Mundo|language=es|date=20 July 2015|access-date=28 June 2019}}</ref> He became manager of the [[Spain national under-21 football team|under-21 side]] in July 2018, after [[Albert Celades]] resigned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldesmarque.com/bizkaia/athletic-club/172072-luis-de-la-fuente-candidato-a-seleccionador-sub-21-2|title=OFICIAL: Luis de la Fuente seleccionador sub 21|trans-title=OFFICIAL: Luis de la Fuente under-21 manager|publisher=El Desmarque|language=es|date=24 July 2018|access-date=31 March 2019}}</ref> His first competition was the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2019 European Championship]] in Italy, conquered after the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|2–1 final]] defeat of [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in [[Udine]].<ref name=U21>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/30/spain-germany-euro-u21-final-match-report|title=Classy Spain sink Germany to lift Euro Under-21 Championship|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Ben|last=Fisher|date=30 June 2019|access-date=1 July 2019}}</ref>

On 8 June 2021, de la Fuente and his team filled in as the [[Spain national football team|Spain senior side]] for a [[UEFA Euro 2020]] [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], after the aforementioned squad had gone into isolation when [[Sergio Busquets]] tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2021/06/07/seleccion/1623079987_818173.html|title="Estoy preparado si tengo que dirigir a la Selección en la Eurocopa"|trans-title="I'm prepared if I have to lead the national team at the Euros"|newspaper=Diario AS|first1=Javier|last1=G. Matallanas|first2=Sergio|last2=Santos Chozas|language=es|date=7 June 2021|access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref> They won 4–0 in [[Leganés]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/espana-vs-lituania/cronica/2021/06/08/60bfd85222601dc65d8b458f.html|title=Spain youngsters impress in Lithuania rout|newspaper=Marca|first=Ben|last=Feldman|date=8 June 2021|access-date=9 June 2021}}</ref>

De la Fuente was also in charge of the [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spanish Olympic team]] at the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Olympic Games]] in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/pedri-garcia-torres-among-spains-euro-2020-players-named-in/1c8y6858hfpia1xji4f8ej3pqi|title=Pedri, Garcia & Torres among Spain's Euro 2020 players named in Tokyo Olympics squad|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=29 June 2021|access-date=7 July 2021}}</ref> His side won the silver medal, losing 2–1 to [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil]] in [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Final|the final]].<ref name=OG>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2021/08/07/olympic_games/1628315614_315184.html|title=Tokyo Olympics 2021 medal count updates: who has won more? Tally by country, today, 7 August|newspaper=Diario AS|date=7 August 2021|access-date=20 August 2021}}</ref>

===Spain senior===
On 8 December 2022, de la Fuente was appointed head coach of the senior side, as [[Luis Enrique]] resigned following a round-of-16 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] elimination at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] by [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/world-cup/2022/12/08/6391e553268e3e3f7b8b45c1.html|title=Luis de la Fuente is Spain's new coach, succeeding Luis Enrique|newspaper=Marca|first1=Miguel Ángel|last1=Lara|first2=Diego|last2=Picó|date=8 December 2022|access-date=9 December 2022}}</ref> He was officially presented four days later, with a contract running until [[UEFA Euro 2024]] with the option to be extended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rfef.es/es/noticias/luis-de-la-fuente-en-su-presentacion-va-ser-una-etapa-fantastica|title=Luis de la Fuente, en su presentación: "Va a ser una etapa fantástica"|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente, in his presentation: "This will be a fantastic spell"|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=es|date=12 December 2022|access-date=12 December 2022}}</ref>

De la Fuente won 3–0 in a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|European qualifier]] at home to [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in his first game on 25 March 2023, with two goals by 32-year-old debutant [[Joselu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65076853|title=Spain 3–0 Norway|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=25 March 2023|access-date=26 March 2023}}</ref> He led the country to victory in the [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League]] (a first ever), defeating [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] 5–4 on penalties following a [[2023 UEFA Nations League final|0–0 draw]] in [[Rotterdam]].<ref name=UNL>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65944659|title=Croatia 0–0 Spain (Spain win 5–4 on penalties)|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Emma|last=Smith|date=18 June 2023|access-date=19 June 2023}}</ref>

Spain finished the Euro 2024 group stage in first place, scoring five goals and conceding none.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eldebate.com/deportes/eurocopa/20240627/perfeccion-le-sale-cara-espana-unica-ganado-tres-partidos-no-evita-lado-dificil_208457.html|title=La perfección le sale cara a España: es la única que ha ganado sus tres partidos, pero no evita el lado difícil|trans-title=Perfection comes without a prize for Spain: they are the only won to have won their three matches, but do not avoid top section|publisher=[[El Debate (Spain)|El Debate]]|first=Jorge|last=Herrero|language=es|date=27 June 2024|access-date=9 July 2024}}</ref> De la Fuente's side went on to claim the trophy in [[Berlin]] with seven wins in as many matches, beating [[England national football team|England]] 2–1 in [[UEFA Euro 2024 final|the final]].<ref name=EURO>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cp68zzx8x4rt#Report|title=Spain 2–1 England|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|date=14 July 2024|access-date=14 July 2024}}</ref>

In January 2025, de la Fuente extended his contract until the end of [[UEFA Euro 2028|Euro 2028]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/in-good-hands-luis-de-la-fuente-extends-spain-contract-to-2028-40621741|title=🇪🇸 In Good Hands: Luis de la Fuente extends Spain contract to 2028|publisher=[[OneFootball]]|date=27 January 2025|access-date=28 January 2025}}</ref>

==Style of coaching==
Due to his background coaching in youth setups, de la Fuente liked to work with younger players familiar to him and not high-maintenance. [[Mikel Merino]], [[Dani Olmo]], [[Mikel Oyarzabal]], [[Fabián Ruiz]] and [[Unai Simón]] won the under-21 European championship title during his tenure, and later represented the full team under the same manager.<ref name=TA>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5068100/2023/11/20/spain-luis-de-la-fuente/|title=This is Luis de la Fuente's Spain: Functional, lower-profile and with realistic expectations|publisher=[[The Athletic]]|first=Dermot|last=Corrigan|date=20 November 2023|access-date=19 March 2024}}</ref> He explained his philosophy by stating that "I come from a grassroots background. Our commitment, to the people we trust in the youth system, is not a pose, it is a conviction".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thesun.my/sport/spain-contenders-at-euro-2024-but-need-time-says-de-la-fuente-KE12253595|title=Spain 'contenders' at Euro 2024 but need 'time', says De La Fuente|newspaper=[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]]|date=24 March 2024|access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref>

Spain often dominated possession under de la Fuente, also starting to use a more traditional [[centre-forward]] and delivering more [[Cross (association football)|crosses]] to the box.<ref name=TA/>

==Personal life==
De la Fuente married a woman from [[Andalusia]], with whom he had three children. One son, Alberto, was also involved in the sport, and at one point worked with his father in the [[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] as an analyst.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rtve.es/television/20221212/luis-fuente-familia-mujer-hijos-etaoa-futbolista/2411486.shtml|title=Luis de la Fuente: la vida familiar de un hombre discreto, sin redes sociales y un hijo que se dedica al fútbol|trans-title=Luis de la Fuente: the family life of an unassuming man, without social media and a footballing son|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=es|date=12 December 2022|access-date=18 July 2024}}</ref>

Having been raised Catholic, de la Fuente embraced the religion again in adulthood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/258264/coach-says-making-sign-of-the-cross-before-game-is-not-superstition-it-s-faith|title=Coach says making sign of the cross before game 'is not superstition, it's faith'|publisher=[[Catholic News Agency]]|first=Almudena|last=Martínez-Bordiú|date=12 July 2024|access-date=18 July 2024}}</ref>

